document.title: [Archdiocese of Milwaukee Curriculum Documents (Exit Expectations, Gr3)]

38118FA39E2C4DB38A0268CDCF15B39E.description:
Demonstrate stewardship inspired by
Catholic values in the care of local and global
environments.

4605636CCBC44370AC183991FC2BA7F1.description:
Work cooperatively and respect my
classmates’ ideas, roles, and abilities.

6CD791ACFCF7409EB0C7E6674657678B.description: Use evidence in a claim to support argument.

CFCF7691953B4B3EB4E8069A179B34CB.description:
Argue for or against a solution to a weather
related hazard.

C86CDCFD541844E29B2B33656E73158A.description:
Humans can not eliminate natural hazards but
can take steps to reduce their impact.

6DEA2FD2D2A943DCA64DBFA85D55B900.description:
A variety of natural hazards result from natural
processes.

1C07DB371D14408EB5B3C25D6CF3C3FF.description:
Make a claim about the merit of a
design solution that reduces the impacts of
weather related hazard.
[Clarification Statement: examples of design
solutions to weather related hazards could
include barriers to prevent flooding, wind
resistant roofs, and lightening rods.]

EEF395FF01574926A4FA78DF442247B7.description: EARTH AND SPACE SCIENCES: Earth and Human Activity

673F71861955400096CB6D5160A79828.description:
Obtain information about the weather
patterns of different climates.

6BBDEE7DB65D43AE92A094C90497A1D3.description:
Identify the connection between
weather patterns and climate.

E91838FB144B4B57958AE98B76093B29.description: Describe the climate of a particular area.

06EB204F9FB345ABAEE6514CAC4728DA.description:
Climate describes a range of an area’s
typical weather conditions and the extent to
which those conditions vary over years.

01EADEC0760249309B8C8A2C7A152FB1.description:
Obtain and combine information to
describe climates in different regions of the
world.

2A6EE886A5124AFCADC6742AE0DC5261.description:
Describe the weather conditions during
particular seasons.

18B9B4BD2EF34F63A6B88A26CDE653F8.description:
Represent collected data in a pictograph
or bar graph.

5EABAB163AE14CE19AC859965890BC46.description:
Collect data about weather conditions
during a particular season.

6029C1822F654A37B624FFD025A9F4A9.description:
Scientists record patterns of weather
across different times and areas so that they
can make predictions about what kind of
weather might happen next.

56A346D111F54A15998F460C1971DEF3.description:
Represent data in tables and
geographical displays to describe typical
weather conditions expected during a particular
season.
[Clarification Statement- examples of data could
include average temperature, precipitation, and
wind direction. The geographical displays are
limited to pictographs and bar graphs. Does not
include climate change.]

C03C342E736D4633A3A0513702A816C6.description: EARTH AND SPACE SCIENCES: Earth’s Systems

63226878B35148129BD66AD98F0FD42F.description:
Work cooperatively and respect my classmates’
ideas, roles, and abilities.

CB2CFE9989D44BFC9F4C5916EAD1D04C.description:
Demonstrate stewardship inspired by Catholic
values in the care of local and global
environments.

92B3C4C430A14CBBA3A2CAADF2DA4E8E.description:
Discuss the theory of evolution and origin of life
in the context of Catholic teaching.

EC320C9C33564002A9199A98B6C1C119.description:
Relate concepts of heredity and reproduction to
life and dignity of the human person.

32C4FB83DA344C3E8CC00F9C9498BA4D.description:
Design and support a solution to an
environmental change that impacts plants and
animals.

984E3C00656C4178BCA9DC03BCEF7D56.description:
Explain how changes in the environment such
as pollution, natural disasters, and climate
change can impact organisms.

8DACE6DDE05B4492B1200625DA3D7642.description:
Populations live in a variety of habitats, and
change in those habitats affects the organisms
living there.

C799D40E28AE44A39F8DFBC09FE22DBD.description:
Make a claim about the merit of a solution
to a problem caused when the environment changes
and the types of plants and animals that live there
may change.

ED9BAFB7E8804F1CB9BAFAFECFA14440.description:
Analyze the cause and effect relationships
within a habitat.

9B734A3768444111B8E5E14F2481E8F5.description:
Support an argument that organisms depend on
each other for survival through modeling,
illustrating, or creating a diagram.

1FA8A9D05E5F46299E262F337B50A3E5.description:
Define a habitat as an environment in which an
animal lives.

B8A6D9BBFE18483F9DC2CFD42B4F8EB5.description: State what animals need to survive.

439E4D2B85DA4601927CEC992829A600.description:
When the environment changes in ways that affect
a place’s physical characteristics, temperature, or
availability of resources, some organisms survive
and reproduce, others move to new locations or
die.

5247AEDEF6E9457E8BF8459505CD8B4D.description:
Construct an argument with evidence that in
a particular habitat some organisms can survive well,
some survive less well, and some cannot survive at
all.
[Clarification Statement: Examples of evidence could
include needs and characteristics of the organisms
and habitats involved. The organisms and their
habitat make up a system in which the parts depend
on each other.]

EA4297C3E2E94D378230D8840C9AB121.description:
Identify variations among the same species,
such as differences in fur coat or coloration for
attracting a mate.

B4B3D3831DFA4B1B8918A16F6FD445A0.description:
Formulate an explanation of how some
organisms survive better in an environment
based on their characteristics.

B3E8003F2C36401BA6245B4D048CE9AF.description:
Sometimes the difference in characteristics
between individuals of the same species provide
advantages in surviving, finding mates and
reproducing.

1EA81BDBB6B24C2FB09CD4EE673E39F0.description:
Use evidence to construct an explanation for
how the variations in characteristic among individuals
of the same species may provide advantage in
surviving, finding mates, and reproducing.

AC37E677035C4D3DA25B980DD74456E1.description:
Describe/compare life from the fossil record
with modern life forms.

99E64ADD3A9B435793A057BDF8D0C3BA.description:
Interpret the significance of different types of
fossil remain.

0451696F48704BA0B2D26ABEFFA3740B.description:
Analyze and interpret data from fossils about
the environments from long ago.

82F3589153BE4D018A2A52205B83BFD6.description:
Some kinds of plants and animals that once lived
on Earth are no longer found anywhere.

870FC83242AD404AA8EAA055BD6BDDFC.description:
Fossils provide evidence about the types of plants
and animals that lived long ago.

58957C0E67ED447EA47F1BE2F7C0469E.description:
Analyze and interpret data from fossils to
provide evidence of the organisms and the
environments in which they lived long ago.

2171DEE7284C4B9D9438E46B13821E99.description: LIFE SCIENCE: Biological Evolution: Unity and Diversity

C4EC44420025469CA74AF4B73E83198C.description:
Summarize the cause and effect relationship
between an organism's traits and its
environment.

1847675DE3FA4B9FA05D024E14FC9DE9.description:
Use evidence to infer how the environment can
negatively affect an organism's traits.

1D5D9470384D4DB389D74CFB6D50C007.description:
Environment affects the traits that an organism
develops.

202935BFA17945749FD93283BFEDD69C.description:
Some characteristics result from individuals’
interaction with the environment.

E05D5B1BEBB14C5D89ADE18A2EE7D797.description:
Use evidence to support the explanation
that traits can be influenced by the environment.
[Clarification Statement: Examples of the
environment affecting a trait could include normally
tall plants grown with insufficient water are stunted;
and, a pet dog that is given too much food and little
exercise may become overweight.]

E6D31EE32DD7416CB6DFB65F1CACC596.description:
Identify the passing of physical traits from
parent to offspring such as fur color, ear shape,
nose shape, teeth, height, etc.

31270DF5F5E841C4B9BD2FAB73E73A49.description:
Analyze patterns of physical traits between
offspring and their parents (organisms other
than humans).

7D61652768924F54B123B1BA6B3D1879.description:
Different organisms vary in how they look and
function because they have different inherited
information.

55F9BF68F8EC499DB6609F6EAAF0F0D9.description:
Many characteristics of organisms are inherited
from their parents.

6E94F54AE0FB4505BFD2D88AF5803200.description:
Analyze and interpret data to provide
evidence that plants and animals have traits inherited
from parents and that variations of these traits exist
in a group of similar organisms.
[Clarification Statement: Patterns are the similarities
and differences in traits shared between offspring
and their parents, or among siblings. Emphasis is on
organisms other than humans.]

0FDDDF808521497897579C57BB688642.description: LIFE SCIENCE: Heredity: Inheritance and Variation of Traits

5D1E613CC17B429D89860C6454579125.description:
Provide evidence that some animals survive
better in groups.

6B01983829B348DBBF7DB31CC0C8408E.description: Explain the advantage of belonging to a group.

5B5484D61F434A1DBA324FE46E38FA41.description: List various groups to which animals belong.

B60CF5E2A710497E99B9B544C496CDE5.description:
Groups may serve different functions and vary
dramatically in size.

8C593418D123485F873241184494E5F7.description:
Being a part of a group helps animals obtain food,
defend themselves, and cope with changes.

1F99C02728E742E2A072633B2550D0F7.description:
Construct an argument that some animals
form groups that help members survive.

EDA5807822CD4968AAEDD7810FE1B81C.description: LIFE SCIENCE: Ecosystems: Interactions, Energy, and Dynamics

83547DECD1A845BDB90BBC7521DA0458.description: Develop a model of a life cycle.

46EA4E4C135C43DE9B097ECAFB73464D.description: Explain the life cycle of flowering plants.

FCEB73D3A627469FAD3F8B4D978E0E2B.description:
Identify the progression of life for plants and
animals as: birth, growth and development,
reproduction, death (animals, not human
reproduction).

53D814A8785F461394247EA321367D95.description:
Organisms all go through birth, growth,
reproduction, and death.

D8AF2DFE152240BFA53F040551DEB353.description:
Reproduction is essential to the continued
existence of every kind of organism.

1BF3156DDA324F49952069BEE52BA384.description:
Plants and animals have unique and diverse life
cycles.

78EC0CEEB40A4683B7B7E095A3BECBF9.description:
Develop models to describe that organisms
have unique and diverse life cycles but all have in
common birth, growth, reproduction, and death.
[Clarification Statement: Changes organisms go
through during their life form a pattern.]

21F53D8CB16B4102A715B4E28B3F0298.description: LIFE SCIENCE: From Molecules to Organisms: Structures and Processes

ACBD86B3F05B4CED812256833825D70B.description:
Work cooperatively and respect my
classmates’ ideas, roles, and abilities.

C00AD35F28754096BC2F24E698369B2F.description:
Show the solution to the design problem using
magnets.

18DA65B15C98480196A6EDB1B05D84B9.description:
Identify a design problem that can be solved
by using magnets.

95244DF05F484E76BA14FA31EFAD0D78.description:
The sizes of the forces in each situation
depend on the properties of the objects and
their distances apart and, for forces between
two magnets, on their orientation relative to
each other.

043B386E3D004F9C8FF1D21551FBD7BA.description:
Magnetic forces between a pair of objects do
not require that the objects be in contact.

76B6223DECA64F0785F097A3DABE40FA.description:
Define a simple design problem that can
be solved by applying scientific ideas about
magnets.
[Clarification Statement: Examples of problems
could include constructing a latch to keep a door
shut and creating a device to keep moving
objects from touching each other.]

86FD6B9F9D9F4AEDA3023DCA6090B0D7.description:
Demonstrate the relationship between
distance and strength of the force.

3641670AF350443D9BE7FEE91DACFF65.description:
Recognize that electric and magnetic forces
between a pair of objects does not require
contact.

EBB1EA45E09A49969A67CE5105A91E7E.description:
Generate questions about how distance or
orientation effect electric and magnetic forces.

B7DD58F9016D4F1EB8F6D336A40F6EC7.description:
The sizes of the forces in each situation
depend on the properties of the objects and
their distances apart and, for forces between
two magnets, on their orientation relative to
each other.

7885125FAFB44EC6B95F69CD42418674.description:
Electric and magnetic forces between a pair of
objects do not require that the objects be in
contact.

6DEF50CC9E3049AD8A8F27103CEDAC92.description: Objects in contact exert forces on each other.

FC97D0E0C96C4770AB3985DAABB69438.description:
Ask questions to determine cause and
effect relationships of electric or magnetic
interactions between two objects not in contact
with each other.

E56ED90CF6684923B690E7AA39A82556.description:
Use observations to predict the future motion
of an object.

6423342EE69640F3949F9FF650A7276B.description: Observe the pattern of an object's motion.

6C52CC6B2E984F7D9348AA180AD919BE.description:
When past motion exhibits a regular pattern,
future motion can be predicted from it.

00418878C0CD4CA3BD8031C5ED6A9C57.description:
The patterns of an object’s motion in various
situations can be observed and measured.

74F8F4BFAF5D486182A3D1D4F225EE07.description:
Make observations and/or
measurements of an object’s motion to provide
evidence that a pattern can be used to predict
future motion.
[Clarification Statement: examples of motion
with a predictable pattern could include a child
swinging in a swing, and two children on a
seesaw. Assessment does not include technical
terms such as period and frequency. ]

EF876EFCA7B145D4A55625D1DBB91A62.description:
Investigate forces with a partner and record
the data.

786AEAB81E8D422EBCE65D7C22C845B0.description:
Identify the effects of balanced forces and
unbalanced forces on objects.

A2E5602F8E894A5F86B197A2D8FE7144.description: Explain that a force is a push or a pull.

F801760AFCEB43F08EDAFF3549DF167B.description:
Unbalanced forces result in the movement of
an object.

4C7D8776163347CFA246C5948677A750.description:
Equal balanced forces do not change an
object’s speed or direction of motion.

AD71D35D0C034B3BA18E4CCE0496AA96.description:
An object at rest typically has multiple forces
acting on it, but they do not result in
movement.

A6B6EFA5B86E4DE6B4F7CC60562404CD.description:
Each force acts on one particular object and
has both strength and a direction.

D90259DB7B134041AFF3BC5D4E734B87.description:
Plan and conduct an investigation to
provide evidence of the effects of balanced and
unbalanced forces on the motion of an object.

E24346A527CE444A9CDE0F22A477071C.description: PHYSICAL SCIENCE: Motion and Stability: Forces and Interactions
